# AIV Protocol — Rules for AI Coding Assistants

This project uses the AIV Protocol for evidence-based code verification.
Do NOT use plain `git commit` for functional code changes. Use `aiv commit` instead.

## Commit Workflow

1. `aiv begin <name> -d "<description>"` — Start a tracked change
2. `git add <file>` — Stage the file
3. `aiv commit <file> -m "<message>" -t R1 -c "<claim>" -i "<url>" --requirement "<req>" -r "<rationale>" -s "<summary>"` — Commit with evidence
4. Repeat 2-3 for each file
5. `aiv close --requirement "<req>"` — Generate verification packet
6. `git push`

## Critical Rules

- Claims (-c) MUST be falsifiable: "TokenValidator rejects expired tokens with 401" NOT "Fixed auth bug"
- Intent (-i) MUST be a URL (https://...), not plain text
- R1+ commits are BLOCKED if >50% of claims lack test coverage. Use --force "justification" to override.
- --skip-checks is ONLY allowed for R0 (docs, formatting, comments)
- Run `aiv quickstart` for the full workflow reference

## Files That Don't Need aiv commit

- .md files in docs/ (unless they're specifications)
- .github/aiv-evidence/ files (generated by aiv commit)
- .github/aiv-packets/ files (generated by aiv close)
- .aiv.yml, .cursorrules, .windsurf/ (config files)

## Risk Tiers

- R0: Trivial (docs, comments, formatting)
- R1: Low risk (bug fixes, refactors) — default
- R2: Medium (API changes, config, deps)
- R3: High (auth, crypto, payments, PII)
